To create a http connection with cloud server to transmit or receive data:

Library: HTTP.Client
#include <HTTPClient.h>

->to configure esp32 with the web address we want to communicate with:
http.begin(WiFiClient, "http://your-server.com/api")
For more secure connection with https:-
http.begin(WiFiClientSecure, "https://your-server.com/api")
http.begin() will return a bool value: true if intitalisation format is correct and false if URL format is wrong.

-> http.end():
 Closes the current network connection and releases all memory allocated by the HTTP client back to the ESP32 system.
It returns nothing

-> http.setTimeout():
What it does: Sets the maximum time (in milliseconds) the ESP32 will wait for the cloud server to respond to a request before giving up.
Syntax: http.setTimeout(10000) (Sets a 10-second timeout window)
Returns: Nothing (void).

->http.addHeader():
To add the header :- most general header calls-
1) http.addHeader ("Content-Type", "applicatioin/json")
Tells server what format your data is in
Without this, the server will not know how to parse the data that we put in .
"application/json" — JSON data
"application/x-www-form-urlencoded" — Form data
"text/plain" — Plain text
"text/xml" — XML data

2) http.addHeader("Authorization","Bearer <api_token");
For Aunthenticated API, where token is necessary.

3) http.addHeader("accept", "application/json");
 Tells server what format you want in response

We can have musltiple headers in single code, each one serving one purpose.

DATA sending functions:
The functions will return an integer - that is the http status code . 200 for success, 404 : not found, negative number for low level hardware or network error.

a) http.GET:
What it does: Sends a request to the server to fetch/retrieve information.
Syntax: int httpCode = http.GET();
Returns: int (HTTP Status Code).

b) http.POST():
What it does: Sends a request containing a data payload to the cloud server to create or update a record.
Syntax Options: * http.POST(String_Payload) (To send text formats like JSON)
http.POST(uint8_t * buffer, size_t size) (To send raw binary or bytes, like a camera image frame)
Returns: int (HTTP Status Code).

c) http.PUT()
What it does: Sends data to a server designed specifically to replace or update an existing resource or database line.
Syntax: http.PUT(String_Payload)
Returns: int (HTTP Status Code).

Responsde retrieval functions:
After action based functions like GET(), POST(),
To get receive the response from the website :-

a)http.getString()
What it does: Downloads the entire response payload from the cloud server and converts it into a single Arduino String.
Syntax: String response = http.getString();
Returns: String containing the server's reply message.
Note: Best used for short server replies like confirmation messages or small JSON objects.

b)http.getSize()
What it does: Checks the Content-Length header sent back by the server to see exactly how many bytes of data are waiting to be read.
Syntax: int payloadSize = http.getSize();
Returns: int (Size of the incoming payload in bytes).

c) http.getStream()
What it does: Returns a direct operational hook to the raw underlying network stream.
Syntax: WiFiClient& stream = http.getStream();
Returns: A reference to the WiFiClient network stream object.
Note: Critical for advanced robotics applications. Instead of loading a massive data file into the ESP32's limited RAM all at once via getString(), getStream() lets you read and process incoming server data byte-by-byte.


So the functions in HTTPClient library are:
Initialization function : http.begin(WiFiClient, "http://server.api");
Header functions : http.addHeader () : telling what dtype we are going to input ("Content-Type"), what dtype we input from website ("accept"), authorization by api token, etc
Action based functions: http.GET(), http.POST(), http.PUT()
response retrieval functions








